RELATION OF THE XCT COMPUTED TOMOGRAPHY WITH THE ULTRASOUND PULSE ECHO¶

Part 1/X¶

GOAL¶

  • Perform and measure the relation between the attenuation C-scan and the porosity projection of the XCT.
    • Measure linear correlation with window = 1mm^2
    • Measure linear correlation with window = 3mm^2

MATERIALS AND DATA¶

There are two origins: data from the reconstructed XCT volume and the attenuation C-scan of the ultrasound volume.

  • Ultrasounds data: The attenuation C-scan measured in pulse-eco.
    XCT Scan
  • XCT porosity projections with size equal to the C-scans.

1.1 Measure lineal correlation with window side = 1mm¶

In [6]:
## Window dataframe
l_dfs = [df_c4_w1,df_c5_w1,df_c6_w1,df_c7_w1]


fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,4,figsize=(20,5),sharey=True,sharex=True)
init1=2
init2=4.5
spacing=0.075

for i,df in enumerate(l_dfs):
    df_train = df
    X_train = df_train['att_12_prof'].to_numpy().reshape(-1,1)
    y_train = df_train['porosity']

    # lineal Regression
    linr1 = skl.linear_model.LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True)
    linr1.fit(X_train,y_train)

    # Plotting regression line
    line_por = np.linspace(np.min(X_train),np.max(X_train),2)    # Porosidad
    ylinepor = linr1.predict(line_por.reshape(-1,1))

    ax[i].scatter(X_train,y_train)
    
    ax[i].plot(line_por,ylinepor,'red')
    ax[i].set_ylim( ymin=-0.2, ymax=5)
    ax[i].set_xlim( xmin=0, xmax=30)
    
    
    ## Texts
    # Params
    ax[i].text(init1, init2-spacing,'y = {}*x + {}'.format(np.round(linr1.coef_[0], decimals=3),np.round(linr1.intercept_, decimals=3)))
    ax[i].text(init1, init2-4*spacing,'R2 = {}'.format(np.round(linr1.score(X_train,y_train), decimals=3)))
    
    # Axis titles
    fig.text(0.5, -0.10, 'C-scan Attenuation (db)', ha='center', va='center').set_fontsize(20)
    fig.text(0.10, 0.5, 'XCT Porosity (v%)', ha='center', va='center', rotation='vertical').set_fontsize(20)
    
    fig.text(0.20, 0.00, 'Coupon 4', ha='center', va='center').set_fontsize(15)
    fig.text(0.41, 0.00, 'Coupon 5', ha='center', va='center').set_fontsize(15)
    fig.text(0.62, 0.00, 'Coupon 6', ha='center', va='center').set_fontsize(15)
    fig.text(0.83, 0.00, 'Coupon 7', ha='center', va='center').set_fontsize(15)

The results of the lineal fit are displayed in this table

R2 a b
c4 0.36 0.14 -1.27
c5 0.35 0.11 -1.01
c6 0.37 0.11 -1.05
c7 0.25 0.12 -0.73
RESULTS:
  • R2: The lineal regression does not fit the wide variety of data and presents values of R2 below 0.4
  • Coefficients The regression lines of coupon 5 and 6 present very similar coefficients. The coupon 4 one presents a slightly different slope than them.
  • Coupon 7 is different The scatter data and lineal regression show how coupon 7 presents different behaviour than the rest of coupons.

In [ ]:
## Window dataframe
l_dfs = [df_c4_w3,
         df_c5_w3,
         df_c6_w3,
         df_c7_w3]


fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,4,figsize=(20,5),sharey=True,sharex=True)
init1=2
init2=2.8
spacing=0.075

for i,df in enumerate(l_dfs):
    df_train = df
    X_train = df_train['att_12'].to_numpy().reshape(-1,1)
    y_train = df_train['porosity']

    # lineal Regression
    linr1 = skl.linear_model.LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True)
    linr1.fit(X_train,y_train)

    # Plotting regression line
    line_por = np.linspace(np.min(X_train),np.max(X_train),2)    # Porosidad
    ylinepor = linr1.predict(line_por.reshape(-1,1))

    ax[i].scatter(X_train,y_train)
    
    ax[i].plot(line_por,ylinepor,'red')
    ax[i].set_ylim( ymin=-0.2, ymax=3)
    ax[i].set_xlim( xmin=0, xmax=30)
    
    
    ## Texts
    # Params
    ax[i].text(init1, init2-spacing,'y = {}*x + {}'.format(np.round(linr1.coef_[0], decimals=3),np.round(linr1.intercept_, decimals=3)))
    ax[i].text(init1, init2-4*spacing,'R2 = {}'.format(np.round(linr1.score(X_train,y_train), decimals=3)))
    
    # Axis titles
    fig.text(0.5, -0.10, 'C-scan Attenuation (db)', ha='center', va='center').set_fontsize(20)
    fig.text(0.10, 0.5, 'XCT Porosity (v%)', ha='center', va='center', rotation='vertical').set_fontsize(20)
    
    fig.text(0.20, 0.00, 'Coupon 4', ha='center', va='center').set_fontsize(15)
    fig.text(0.41, 0.00, 'Coupon 5', ha='center', va='center').set_fontsize(15)
    fig.text(0.62, 0.00, 'Coupon 6', ha='center', va='center').set_fontsize(15)
    fig.text(0.83, 0.00, 'Coupon 7', ha='center', va='center').set_fontsize(15)

The results of the lineal fit are displayed in this table

R2 a b
c4 0.67 0.14 -1.14
c5 0.65 0.11 -0.99
c6 0.68 0.11 -1.03
c7 0.45 0.12 -0.65
RESULTS:
  • R2: Coupons 4 to 6 show a R2 value of almost 0.7. The graphics show the good fitting of the lineal regression in all the porosity range. Coupon 7 has a lower value, equal to 0.46. The regression line is further of the upper porosity values, the range from 1.5% to the 3%
  • Coefficients The regression lines of coupon 5 and 6 present very similar coefficients. The coupon 4 one presents a slightly different slope.
  • Coupon 7 is still different The fitting has improved from the one of window=1mm2, but for porosity contents above the 1% the model understimates.
  • The porosity distribution With a larger window the porosity distribution is changed and the uppest value no longer surpasses the 3%, whereareas in the window = 1mm2, there were several registers near the 5%.
CONCLUSIONS: Relation of the Computed Tomography (XCT) and the Ultrasound Techniques (UT)
* It is possible to relate the XCT and the ultrasound techniques. * The projection of the reconstructed porosity and the attenuation images are lineally correlated with a sliding window of size equal to 3mm2 for three out of the four coupons. * The coupon 7 presents a different behaviour. The lineal model fails for registers with porosity above 1% * It is clear that the window size affects since the window equal to 1mm2 had R2 below 0.4. The effects of window size needs of further study
